   <abstract >This study examines how Forrest Carlisle Pogue (1912 - 1996) critically influenced the writing of official United States military history and helped validate oral history as a legitimate historical resource in the late twentieth century. Drafted into the Army in 1942, Pogue was handpicked to serve as one of a handful of newly minted combat historians to serve in the United States Army during World War II. With few precedents upon which to rely, Pogue and his fellow combat historians were left to their own devices regarding their mission of collecting historical information in the European Theater of Operations. From a LST floating in the English Channel on D-Day, to Pilzen, Czechoslovakia on V-E Day, Pogue conducted oral history interviews with participants directly from the battlefield and sometimes under direct enemy fire. During the immediate post-war years, Pogue coupled his formal training as a historian with his wartime experience as a combat historian to write The Supreme Command, the third volume in the government-sponsored U.S. Army in World War II series more commonly known today as the "Green Books." In 1956, the George C. Marshall Research Foundation selected Pogue as the executive director for their planned research library and the official biographer of George Catlett Marshall. From 1956 to 1987, Pogue wrote an epic, four-volume biography consisting of George C. Marshall: Education of a General, 1880 - 1939 (1963); George C. Marshall: Ordeal and Hope, 1939 - 1942 (1966); George C. Marshall: Organized of Victory, 1942 - 1945 (1973); and George C. Marshall: Statesman, 1945 - 1959 (1987). In 1988, the Society of American Historians (SAH) recognized Pogue's work with their prestigious Francis Parkman Prize for Special Achievement. Pogue's efforts to utilize oral sources as the foundation for The Supreme Command and the Marshall biography garnered the attention of organizers who were trying to professionalize the burgeoning field of oral history. During the late twentieth century, Pogue became directly involved in establishing the Oral History Association and assisted aspiring oral history groups get their fledgling programs established. Pogue's involvement supported the study and practice of oral history emerge as a legitimate historical resource that continues to evolve.</abstract>
